body:
## Bevy version
0.13

## What you did

Manipulating UI elements sometimes need cleanup. 

## What went wrong

Calling `commands.entity(entity).despawn_recursive();` can cause `taffy` to panic:

```
thread 'Compute Task Pool (10)' panicked at \...\.cargo\registry\src\index.crates.io-6f17d22bba15001f\taffy-0.3.18\src\node.rs:285:25:
invalid SlotMap key used
```

This is apparently because the entity is removed from `taffy` before the relevant children/parent is cleaned up, leaving invalid `SlotMap` keys that cannot be looked up when the child/parent relationship is updated. 

However, the origin of this error is from the initial creation of the node hierarchy, meaning that when the node layout is added, somehow `taffy` doesn't have the right reference. Rendering works fine, but trying to despawn a broken entity regardless of where the despawn is started in the hierarchy from always causes the panic. *Might* be related to entity versions, but it's just a feeling.

## Additional information

After two weeks of pulling all-nighters (and my hair) I have this `EntityCommand` that can safely remove broken entities (naming altered for politeness):

``` rust
struct UntuckThisBirch;
impl EntityCommand for UntuckThisBirch{
    fn apply(self, id: Entity, world: &mut World) {
        let Ok(parent) = world.query::<&Parent>().get(world, id) else {
            return;
        };

        let parent_id = parent.get();
        let Ok(parent_children) = world.query::<&Children>().get(world, parent_id) else {
            return;
        };

        let children: Vec<Entity> = parent_children
            .iter()
            .filter(|child| **child != id)
            .map(|child| *child)
            .collect();
        let mut parent = world.entity_mut(parent_id);
        parent.replace_children(&children);

        world.resource_scope(|world, mut ui_surface: Mut<UiSurface>| {
            let Ok(parent_children) = world.query::<&Children>().get(world, parent_id) else {
                return;
            };

            ui_surface.update_children(parent_id, parent_children);
        });

        world.despawn(id);
    }
}
```

It is called in context like so:

``` rust
commands.entity(entity).despawn_descendants();
commands.entity(entity).add(UntuckThisBirch);
```

NOTE: The above command works, and I can despawn the broken entity _targetedly_. **HOWEVER, calling `despawn_descendants` from higher up in the hierarchy without removing the broken entity first also causes the same panic!**
